\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
A dual to the principal chiral model as a toy model for strongly coupled
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\phi^{4}$
\end_inset

 theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
We consider a two dimensional scalar field theory with a nilpotent current
 algebra, which is dual to the Principal Chiral Model.
 The quantum theory is renormalizable and not asymptotically free: the theory
 is strongly coupled at short distances (encountering a Landau pole).
 We suggest it can serve as a toy model for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\phi^{4}$
\end_inset

 theory in four dimensions, just as the principal chiral model is a useful
 toy model for Yang-Mills theory.
 We find some classical wave solutions that survive the strong coupling
 limit and quantize them by the collective variable method.
 They describe excitations with an unusual dispersion relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\propto|k|^{\frac{1}{3}}$
\end_inset

 .
 Perhaps they are the ``preons'' at strong coupling whose bound states form
 massless particles over long distances.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We study the field theory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Nappi,CurtrightZachos"

\end_inset

 with equations of motion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ddot{\phi}=\lambda\left[\dot{\phi},\phi'\right]+\phi'',\label{eq:FieldEqn}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is valued in a Lie algebra, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:\mathbb{R}^{1,1}\to\underline{SU}(2)$
\end_inset

.
 This follows from the action
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S_{1}\equiv\int\mathcal{L}_{1}dxdt=\int\mathrm{Tr}\left\{ \frac{1}{2\lambda}\dot{\phi}^{2}-\frac{1}{2\lambda}\phi'^{2}+\frac{1}{3}\phi[\dot{\phi},\phi']\right\} dxdt.\label{eq:s1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 limit, these equations admit linear wave solutions.
 But in the high-coupling regime, the theory is dominated by nonlinear effects.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 is closely tied to other models and subjects, which we elaborate on in
 section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:relations"

\end_inset

.
 These include the study of slow light, the Wess-Zumino-Witten (WZW) model,
 and the mathematical theory of hypoelliptic operators.
 Of particular interest in this paper, the model described by 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 is also classically dual to the well-studied principal chiral model, described
 by the action
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{2}=\int\mathcal{L}_{2}dxdt=\frac{1}{2f}\int\mathrm{Tr}\ \left\{ \left(g^{-1}\dot{g}\right)^{2}-c^{2}\left(g^{-1}g'\right)^{2}\right\} dxdt
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\mathbb{R}^{1,1}\to SU(2)$
\end_inset

.
 This is a special case of the nonlinear sigma model, with target space
 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{SU}(2)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Despite their classical equivalence, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{2}$
\end_inset

 lead to entirely different quantum theories.
 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{2}$
\end_inset

 gives an asymptotically free theory: at short distances 
\begin_inset Formula $f\to0$
\end_inset

, giving us free massless excitations.
 But the true particles that survive to long distances are bound states
 of non-zero mass
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PCM"

\end_inset

.
 For this reason, the principal chiral model is often used as a toy model
 for 4-dimensional Yang-Mills theory, notorious in for its mathematical
 complexity.
 Not only do the two theories share similar short-distance behavior, but
 the mass gap in the principal chiral model has served as a proof of concept
 for the conjectured (and well-supported) mass gap in Yang-Mills.
 (Even though neither case has a mathematically rigorous proof, yet.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

, on the other hand, leads to a renormalizable but not asymptotically free
 quantum theory.
 At short distances the coupling constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\to\infty$
\end_inset

, while at long distances we have weakly nonlinear massless excitations.
 It makes sense to use 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 as a 2-D toy model for strongly coupled theories, in particular 4-dimensional
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\phi^{4}$
\end_inset

 theory
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
that is, pure 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\phi^{4}$
\end_inset

 theory, describing a Higgs-like particle with no coupling to fermions
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The behavior of quantum field theories at high coupling is notoriously
 intractable, and the physical meaning of  such theories is still up for
 debate.
 For this reason, it is still necessary to search for simple examples of
 such theories and try to gleam what meaning, if any, they have in the short
 distance limit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to sharing short-distance behavior, both the 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 model and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\phi^{4}$
\end_inset

 theory can be recast as quadratic hamiltonians with a step-3 nilpotent
 bracket algebra, suggesting some algebraic structure in common (appendix
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Appendix:nilpotent"

\end_inset

 discusses nilpotent algebra).
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 model's relative simplicity makes it a good candidate for attempting to
 probe the high coupling regime of field theories in general, but the connection
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\phi^{4}$
\end_inset

 theory seems the closest.
 Additionaly, its classical duality to the principal chiral model motivates
 a juxtaposition of the two theories in the classical and quantum cases.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To glimpse what becomes of our theory in the high coupling limit, we take
 the modest approach of finding nonlinear wave-type solutions to the classical
 model which survive the 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 limit (section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Reduction-mech"

\end_inset

).
 This set of solutions defines a mechanical system or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

reduced system
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in each of the dual models.
 While they physically appear very different, the resulting classical solutions
 can be mapped from one system to another.
 We quantize these collective variables to determine their dispersion relation
 (section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:reduced_system_quant"

\end_inset

) in the short distance limit for each theory.
 We have in mind the sine-Gordon theory, whose solitons turns out to be
 the fundamental constituents which bind to form the scalar particles
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "sineGordon,QuantThSolitons"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These reduced quantum theories yield two different results.
 In particular, the reduced model of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 has an exotic dispersion relation in the short distance limit.
 We postulate that its spectrum may hint at the fundamental constituents
 of the highly coupled theory, which need not behave like traditional particles
 at all.
 In section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Conclusion-and-future"

\end_inset

 we offer concluding remarks and a side-by-side comparison of our work with
 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
On The Notation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We regard 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\frac{1}{2i}\left[\phi_{1}\sigma_{1}+\phi_{2}\sigma_{2}+\phi_{3}\sigma_{3}\right]=\frac{1}{2i}\boldsymbol{\phi}\cdot\boldsymbol{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 as a traceless anti-hermitian matrix.
 Recall then that the commutator and cross product are related by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[X,Y]=\frac{1}{2i}\left(\mathbf{X}\times\mathbf{Y}\right)\cdot\boldsymbol{\sigma}.
\]

\end_inset

Also, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Tr}X\equiv-2\mathrm{tr}X$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{Tr}\phi^{2}=\phi_{1}^{2}+\phi_{2}^{2}+\phi_{3}^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

In relativistically invariant notation, (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FieldEqn"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:s1"

\end_inset

) can be written as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}\phi_{a}-\frac{\lambda}{2}\ \epsilon_{abc}\epsilon^{\mu\nu}\partial_{\mu}\phi^{b}\partial_{\nu}\phi^{c}=0,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{1}=\frac{1}{2\lambda}\int\partial_{\mu}\phi^{a}\partial_{\nu}\phi^{a}\eta^{\mu\nu}d^{2}x+\frac{1}{6}\int\epsilon_{abc}\phi^{a}\partial_{\mu}\phi^{b}\partial_{\nu}\phi^{c}\epsilon^{\mu\nu}d^{2}x
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu,\nu=0,1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c=1,2,3$
\end_inset

 ; also, 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon^{\mu\nu},\epsilon_{abc}$
\end_inset

 are the Levi-Civita tensors.
 This is a particular case of the general sigma model studied in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SigmaModelString"

\end_inset

 as the background of string theory, with a flat metric on the target space
 and a constant 3-form field 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{abc}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
relation to other models 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:relations"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The 
\begin_inset Formula $c\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 Limit and Slow Light
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Relation-to-Slow"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the equations of motion (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FieldEqn"

\end_inset

) where the speed of linear propagation at low coupling is taken to be 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 rather than 1: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ddot{\phi}=\lambda\left[\dot{\phi},\phi'\right]+c^{2}\phi''.\label{eq:field_eqn_c}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If we rescale 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\to\lambda^{a}\phi$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t\to\lambda^{b}t$
\end_inset

, this becomes 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda^{a-2b}\ddot{\phi}=\lambda^{1+2a-b}\dot{\phi}\times\phi'+c^{2}\lambda^{a}\phi''.
\]

\end_inset

Set 
\begin_inset Formula $a=2b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1+2a=b$
\end_inset

 to get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ddot{\phi}=\dot{\phi}\times\phi'+c^{2}\lambda^{-\frac{2}{3}}\phi''.
\]

\end_inset

Thus the strong coupling limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\to\infty$
\end_inset

 at fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $c\to0$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ddot{\phi}=\dot{\phi}\times\phi'.\label{eq:StrongCouplingEqn}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The strongly coupled limit can be thought of as the limit in which the waves
 move very slowly.
 It has been noted in that literature 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SlowLight"

\end_inset

 that when the speed of light in a medium is small, nonlinear effects are
 magnified.
 Although the specific equations appearing there are different, it is possible
 that the solutions of the sort we study are of interest in that context
 as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From a field theoretic context, the equivalence of these limits seems troubling.
 At short distances, the highly-coupled theory will not be relativistic.
 It is a sort of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

post-relativistic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 regime, where 
\begin_inset Formula $c\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

.
 This is much the opposite of the case in the theory of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{2}$
\end_inset

, where a mass gap means that the particles which survive to long distances
 are massive; they can be non-relativistic in the traditional 
\begin_inset Formula $c\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 sense.
 Perhaps some such exotic excitations at high coupling are in fact the fundament
al constituents, forming as bound states the ordinary massless particles
 which appear in the long distance limit.
 As we know from the quark model, the short distance excitations do not
 need to be particles in the usual sense; they could be confined.
 In any case, it is important what solutions might survive the high coupling
 limit, whether they be unphysical or simply unintuitive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will see an example of wave solutions which classically survive the 
\begin_inset Formula $c\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 limit, continuing to propagate through nonlinearity alone.
 Since the energy density is constant, these solutions do not violate causality:
 they are analogous to the Continuous Wave solutions in a medium where the
 phase velocity is greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Sub-Riemannian Geometry and the Hormander Condition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The orbits of many mechanical systems can be thought of as geodesics in
 some appropriate Riemannian manifold.
 In the limit of strong coupling, this metric degenerates and can become
 sub-Riemannian.
 That is, the contravariant metric tensor has some zero eigenvalues so that
 it can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j}X_{j}\otimes X_{j}$
\end_inset

 for some vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{j}$
\end_inset

 whose linear span may be smaller than the tangent space.
 If these vector fields satisfy the Hormander condition (i.e.,
\begin_inset Formula $X_{j}$
\end_inset

 along with their repeated commutators span the tangent spaces at every
 point) there still are geodesics connecting every pair of sufficiently
 close points (Chow-Rashevskii theorem)
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "subRiemannian"

\end_inset

.
 This geometry came to the notice of many physicists as a model for self-propuls
ion of amoeba
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ShapereWilczek"

\end_inset

.
 It has its roots in Carnot-Caratheodory geometric formalism of thermodynamics
 and in control theory.
 Hormander
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hormander"

\end_inset

 discovered independently that the same criterion is sufficient for the
 subRiemannian Laplace operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=\sum_{j}X_{j}^{2}$
\end_inset

 to be hypoelliptic: the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 to the inhomogenous equation 
\begin_inset Formula $Lf=u$
\end_inset

 is smooth whenever the source 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is smooth.
 This can be thought of the quantum version of the above condition on subgeodesi
c connectivity: the subRiemannian Laplacian is the quantum hamiltonian of
 a system whose orbits are subRiemannian geodesics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Understanding the strong coupling limit of quantum field theories is a central
 problem of modern theoretical physics.
 It would be nice to have a geometric formulation analogous to the above
 for quantum field theories: seek an infinite dimensional subRiemannian
 manifold whose geodesics are the solutions of the strong coupled limit
 of the classical field theory.
 The subRiemannian Laplacian would be the quantum hamiltonian of this limit.
 This paper presents the simplest example of such a field theory.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since we are trying to minimize the mathematical content in this paper,
 we will not elaborate further on this point, although it underlies everything(s
ee the Appendix for a bit more detail).
 For example, the reduction to the mechanical system below yields a finite
 dimensional system satisfying the Hormader criterion in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Its quantum hamiltonian (in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\to\infty$
\end_inset

 taken as in the previous section) is a hypoelliptic operator, an of Hormander's
 theory.We hope to apply this idea to other challenging strongly coupled
 field theories of physics (e.g., fluid mechanics).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Relation to the WZW model 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also regard our equations as a limiting case of the Wess-Zumino-Witten
 model
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Witten's Tr is our tr.
 His 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is our 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Witten"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{WZW}=\frac{1}{4\lambda_{1}^{2}}\int\mathrm{tr}\ \partial^{\mu}g\partial_{\mu}g^{-1}d^{2}x+\frac{n}{24\pi}\int_{M_{3}}\mathrm{tr}\ (g^{-1}dg)^{3}
\]

\end_inset

as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}\to0$
\end_inset

, keeping 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\lambda_{1}^{2}\left(n/2\pi\right)^{\frac{2}{3}}$
\end_inset

 fixed
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{3}$
\end_inset

 is a 3-manifold of which the two-dimensional space-time is the boundary.
 We do not require 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}^{2}$
\end_inset

 to take the conformally invariant value 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{4\pi}{n}$
\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 To see this, let 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=e^{bi\sigma_{a}\phi^{a}(x)}$
\end_inset

 and expand in powers of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{WZW}=\frac{b^{2}}{2\lambda_{1}^{2}}\int\partial^{\mu}\phi^{a}\partial_{\mu}\phi^{a}+\frac{n}{24\pi}b^{3}\int_{M_{3}}2\epsilon_{abc}\ d\phi^{a}d\phi^{b}d\phi^{c}\ +\cdots
\]

\end_inset

To this order the WZW term is an exact differential, so we can write it
 as an integral over space-time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{WZW}=\frac{1}{2}\frac{b^{2}}{\lambda_{1}^{2}}\int\partial^{\mu}\phi^{a}\partial_{\mu}\phi^{a}+\frac{n}{12\pi}b^{3}\int\epsilon_{abc}\ \phi^{a}d\phi^{b}d\phi^{c}\ +\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $S_{WZW}$
\end_inset

 reduces to 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 if we identify 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{3}=2\pi/n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 as above.
 By taking this limit, we can easily get the renormalization of our model.
 Recall that 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Witten"

\end_inset

 the one loop renormalization group equation of the 
\begin_inset Formula $O(N)$
\end_inset

 WZW model is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\lambda_{1}^{2}}{d\log\Lambda}=-\frac{\lambda_{1}^{4}(N-2)}{2\pi}\left[1-\left(\frac{\lambda_{1}^{2}n}{4\pi}\right)^{2}\right]
\]

\end_inset

We need the particular case of 
\begin_inset Formula $N=4$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the target space being 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{3}\approx SU(2)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus in our limit 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}\to0$
\end_inset

 keeping 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 fixed,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\lambda}{d\log\Lambda}=\frac{\lambda^{4}}{4\pi}
\]

\end_inset

It is useful to take this limit rather than calculating loop corrections
 from scratch, as the renormalization group evolution of the WZW has been
 studied to high order 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bos,Xi"

\end_inset

.
 Including these higher order terms does not alter the short-distance divergence
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Duality with the principal chiral model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have now seen that 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 is strongly coupled in the short-distance limit.
 Yet, as a classical field theory, this can be viewed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Nappi"

\end_inset

 as a dual to the asymptotically free principal chiral model with equation
 of motion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial^{\mu}[g^{-1}\partial_{\mu}g]=0,\quad g:R^{1,1}\to SU(2).
\]

\end_inset

To see this, we define the currents
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I=\frac{1}{\lambda}\dot{\phi},\quad J=\phi'
\]

\end_inset

so the equations of motion become
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dot{J}=\lambda I',\quad\dot{I}=\lambda[I,J]+\frac{1}{\lambda}J'.\label{eq:eqmo}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We can solve the second equation with the relations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I=\frac{1}{\lambda^{2}}g^{-1}g',\quad J=\frac{1}{\lambda}g^{-1}\dot{g},\quad g:\mathbb{R}^{2}\to SU(2).\label{eq:dual}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then the first equation becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{0}\left[g^{-1}\dot{g}\right]=\partial_{1}\left[g^{-1}g'\right]
\]

\end_inset

which is the non-linear sigma model.
 Thus, the same classical equations of motion follow from the action
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{2}=\int\mathcal{L}_{2}dxdt=\frac{1}{2f}\int\mathrm{Tr}\ \left\{ \left(g^{-1}\dot{g}\right)^{2}-c^{2}\left(g^{-1}g'\right)^{2}\right\} dxdt
\]

\end_inset

if we identify 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\lambda^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 A summary of relevant correspondences in the dual models can be found at
 the end of section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Conclusion-and-future"

\end_inset

.
