\begin_layout Standard
Many classical systems have Poisson brackets (or commutators in the quantum
 case) which generate a Lie algebra with a quadratic Hamiltonian: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H=\frac{1}{2}h^{ab}v_{a}v_{b}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ v_{a},v_{b}\right\} =c_{ab}^{c}v_{c}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{ab}^{c}$
\end_inset

 are the structure constants of the bracket algebra and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{a}$
\end_inset

 the dynamical variables.
 The quadratic nature of the Hamiltonian immediately affords a geometric
 interpretation: 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{ab}$
\end_inset

 defines a left-invariant metric, 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in\underline{G}\vee\underline{G}$
\end_inset

 on the Lie group 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{G}$
\end_inset

.
 The equations of motion then describe geodesics on the Lie group under
 this metric.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A nilpotent Lie Algebra of step 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is a Lie algebra in which all repeated brackets of order 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 vanish.
 The combination of a quadratic Hamiltonian 
\emph on
and 
\emph default
a nilpotent bracket algebra can allow one to solve for the spectrum of a
 quantum system algebraically, using only the representation structure of
 the associated Lie group.
 This is done by using a representation to generate raising and lowering
 operators, as is familiar in the case of the harmonic oscillator.
 While we did not take this (somewhat ambitious) approach here, it is carried
 out in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "JorgensenKlink1"

\end_inset

 for a magnetic system very similar to the one we discuss in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:reduced_system_quant"

\end_inset

.
 It is worth at least mentioning this point of view, as it connects the
 model studied here to other, more well-known models.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Nilpotent Mechanical Systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest system of this type is a harmonic oscillator, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H=\frac{1}{2}\left(p^{2}+\omega^{2}q^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ p,q\right\} =1.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here the canonical variables 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 form a step-2 nilpotent Lie algebra, where all double commutators vanish.
 Of course, any Hamiltonian in terms of the canonical variables will have
 this bracket algebra, but what happens in the non-quadratic case? Consider
 the anharmonic oscillator, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H=\frac{1}{2}\left(p^{2}+\omega^{2}q^{2}\right)+\lambda q^{4}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can recast this as a quadratic Hamiltonian with step-3 nilpotent bracket
 algebra by defining 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}=q^{2}$
\end_inset

, and then treating this as a distinct variable in the algebra.
 We then have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H=\frac{1}{2}\left(p^{2}+\omega^{2}q^{2}\right)+\lambda q_{2}^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ p,q_{2}\right\} =2q,\quad\left\{ p,q\right\} =1,\quad\left\{ q_{2},q\right\} =0,
\]

\end_inset

where one can see that all triple commutators vanish.
 Thus, the classical anharmonic oscillator describes geodesics in the correspond
ing nilpotent Lie group.
 It is possible to solve such quantum theories using representations of
 the Lie algebra (as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "JorgensenKlink1"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mechanical reduction of our field theory gives another example.
 The equations of motion (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eqmo_ansatz"

\end_inset

) follow from the hamiltonian (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ham_Ansatz"

\end_inset

) with Poisson Brackets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ S_{a},S_{b}\right\} =\lambda\epsilon_{abc}L_{c},\quad\left\{ L_{a},L_{b}\right\} =0,\quad\left\{ S_{a},L_{b}\right\} =\epsilon_{abc}K_{c}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This a step three nilpotent Lie algebra.
 Its on the space of functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is what we used to quantize the theory.
 In the dual picture the Poisson brackets would not be nilpotent: the Lie
 algebra it is the semi-direct product of 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(2)$
\end_inset

 with an abelian algebra.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Nilpotent Field Theories
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Interestingly, we find that some of the most important field theories of
 particle physics can be described in this way.
 The bosonic part of the standard model consists of Yang-Mills theory coupled
 to a Higgs sector described as a 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\phi^{4}$
\end_inset

 scalar field theory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In field theory, the obvious analogue of the anharmonic oscillator is pure
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\phi^{4}$
\end_inset

 theory.
 Identifying 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}(x)=\phi^{2}(x)$
\end_inset

, this theory can be described by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H=\frac{1}{2}\int\left[\pi^{2}(x)+m^{2}\phi^{2}(x)+\lambda\phi_{2}^{2}\right]dx
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ \pi(x),\phi_{2}(y)\right\} =2\phi(x)\delta(x-y),\quad\left\{ \pi(x),\phi(y)\right\} =\delta(x-y)
\]

\end_inset

Pure 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\phi^{4}$
\end_inset

 theory (without coupling to fermions) in 4 dimensions remains intractable
 in the short distance limit: is not an asymptotically free theory.
 We see here that it follows from a Hamiltonian with one degree of extra
 nilpotency in the bracket algebra.
 This suggests that perhaps the theory is easier tamed with an algebraic
 approach.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another famously puzzling theory, Yang-Mills theory, can be cast in the
 same language.
 Here the Poisson Brackets and Hamiltonian are best expressed in terms of
 the electric field
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E[a]=\int E^{bi}a_{bi}dx
\]

\end_inset

(where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a smooth test function) and the magnetic field 
\begin_inset Formula $B=dA+A\wedge A$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{E[a],B\}=da+[A,a],\quad\{E[a],A\}=a,\quad\{A_{a}(x)_{,}A_{bj}(y)\}=0,\quad H=\frac{1}{2}\int\left(E^{2}+B^{2}\right)dx.
\]

\end_inset

Yang Mills theory, however, is an asymptotically free theory.
 The fact that it can be brought to the same form as pure 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\phi^{4}$
\end_inset

 theory suggests some commonality in structure of the two theories, though
 they might appear glaringly different due to their short-distance behavior.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We pause to note that not all systems are nilpotent.
 The simplest example would be the rigid rotor, whose bracket algebra is
 that of angular momentum, where repeated commutators do not vanish.
 Such a Lie algebra is perhaps misleadingly labeled as 
\emph on
simple
\emph default
 in the mathematics literature.
 Also, the Euler equations of an ideal fluid can be formulated with a quadratic
 hamiltonian on the Lie algebra of vector fields.
 Nilpotent Lie algebras could be useful as approximations here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The current algebra of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equations of motion (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eqmo"

\end_inset

) follow from the hamiltonian
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H_{1}=\frac{1}{2}\int[\lambda I_{a}I_{a}+\frac{1}{\lambda}J^{a}J^{a}]dx
\]

\end_inset

and the Poisson brackets from 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{J^{a}(x),\ J^{b}(y)\}_{1}=0,\quad\{I_{a}(x),\ J^{b}(y)\}_{1}=-\delta_{a}^{b}\delta'(x-y)\quad\{I_{a}(x),\ I_{b}(y)\}_{1}=\epsilon_{abc}J_{c}\delta(x-y).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So this theory can also be cast as a quadratic Hamiltonian with step-3 nilpotent
 algebra.
 This further motivates the analogy between our model and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\phi^{4}$
\end_inset

 theories.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Strong Coupling Limit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is natural, in nilpotent Lie algebras, to take the singular limit of
 the metric where the coefficient of the higher step generators shrink to
 zero.
 (This geometry has been well-studied in the simplest case of the Heisenberg
 group
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "subRiemannian"

\end_inset

).
 This is precisely the strong coupling limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\to\infty$
\end_inset

 of our theory: the second term in the hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\int[\lambda I_{a}I_{a}+\frac{1}{\lambda}J^{a}J^{a}]dx$
\end_inset

 tends to zero.
 In this limit the co-metric is not invertible.
 The resulting sub-Riemannian geometry still has well-defined geodesics.
 This is the geometric meaning of the strongly coupled limit (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:StrongCouplingEqn"

\end_inset

).
 The length of these geodesics still define a metric (e.g., satisfying the
 triangle inequality) on the nilpotent Lie group.
 It would be interesting to look at the strong coupling limits of the other
 examples of nilpotent field theories from this geometric point of view.
\end_layout

